Bring a pan of water to the boil for the noodles. Halve, peel and thinly slice the
@red onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Halve the @green pepper{1} and discard the
core and seeds. Slice into thin strips. Roughly chop the @coriander{1%bunch}(stalks and all).
Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(grated with garlic press). Roughly chop the
@salted peanuts{25%g}(roughly chopped). Trim the @spring onion{1} then slice thinly.

When the pan of water is boiling, add the @egg noodle nest{1} and cook for
~{4%minutes}. Drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to prevent it from
sticking together then set aside.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} over high heat. When the oil is
hot, add the @beef strips{240%g}. Sprinkle on the @Thai style spice mix{1/2%tsp}
(see ingredients for amounts - be careful it's hot!) and stir-fry until browned
but not cooked through, ~{2%minutes}.

> TIP: Do this in batches if your pan is small. You want the steak to brown not stew.

Transfer to a #plate{}, wipe out the pan and return to high heat with a splash of
@oil{}. IMPORTANT: The steak is safe to eat when the outside is cooked.

When the oil is hot, stir-fry the red onions and peppers until slightly softened,
~{4-5%minutes}, adding the garlic for the final minute. Lower the heat and stir in
the @hoisin sauce{50%g}, @soy sauce{25%g}, a splash of @water{} and the noodles.
Bring to a bubble and remove from the heat.

Return the pan to medium heat and stir in the beef strips you browned earlier.
Pour in any steak resting juices. Stir-fry until everything is piping hot and then
mix through the coriander.

Divide the stir-fry between plates and top with the peanuts and sliced spring
onion. Enjoy!